text: Facebook has launched "Facebook News", the latest attempt by the social media giant to support journalism on its site.

title: Facebook Earnings: What to Look For From FB.
text: Facebook (FB) reports Q3 earnings after market close. Look for signs that Facebook is improving the amount of revenue it generates from its users.

title: Facebook unveils new tab in its mobile app dedicated to news stories
text: Facebook Inc. is getting into the news business and paying publishers because it feels it imperative to support a democratic society.

title: Why Facebook’s Libra Cryptocurrency Is In Trouble
text: When Facebook first announced it was getting into the crypto business—with a basically unregulated currency called Libra—the reaction from Wall Street and government bankers was about as expected.

title: Twitter's Dorsey on joining Facebook's Libra: 'Hell no'

text: Business Insider CEO Henry Blodget discusses Facebook's new curated news service as the social media giant fends off controversy surrounding fake news.

title: Facebook Launches News Tab With Dozens Of U.S. Publishers To Combat Fake News
text: Facebook is rolling out its new Facebook News section today, a new tab in the mobile app that is dedicated to solely to news articles.

title: What You Need To Know About The Facebook News Service
text: Facebook, Inc. (NASDAQ: FB) on Friday began testing its new Facebook News project, aimed at better curating what readers see on the platform in a move to address criticism it has allowed misinformation to take over much of the American reading diet.

title: Friday Q3 Earnings Cap a Busy Week
text: More Q3 earnings results are out ahead of Friday's opening bell, capping off the first of several busy weeks of quarterly reportage.

title: Facebook announces dedicated news section
text: Facebook announced a news product as part of a broader push to address criticism for spreading fake news, while also growing an ad business that's stolen marketshare from publishers.

title: Facebook Introduces News Tab In Effort To “Strengthen Democracy”
text: Facebook has launched tests of a “News” tab, which aims to limit the flow of phony stories populating the platform, declaring the ambitious initiative an effort to “strengthen democracy.” The tab will not disrupt the normal functioning of the News Feed or items that appear therein, but it will aim to give users more tools

title: Facebook is 'history being made', says author Walter Isaacson
text: Walter Isaacson, Tulane professor and an advisory partner at Perella Weinberg Partners, joins CNBC's "Squawk Box" team to discuss Facebook's roll out of a news product as well as Verizon and Disney's partnership to offer Verizon customers Disney+ for 12 months.

title: Dryden Pence shares his stock picks for earnings season
text: Dryden Pence, chief investment officer at Pence Wealth Management, joins 'Squawk Box' with his top stock picks and best investment ideas.

title: Facebook News launches in testing phase as local newsrooms fear being left behind
text: Facebook has a message for the skeptical news industry: We're here to help.

title: Facebook starts testing News, its new section for journalism
text: Facebook’s news section, which was previously reported to be imminent, is here: The company is rolling out Facebook News in a limited test. In a blog post, Facebook’s Campbell Brown (vice president of global news partnerships) and Mona Sarantakos (product manager, news) said that news articles will continue to appear in the main News Feed.

title: Facebook News makes its debut as social network battles misinformation
text: The company is testing the news tab in the US first.

title: Facebook Calls Truce With Publishers as It Unveils Facebook News
text: The social network introduced a new section of its mobile app dedicated to news content, offering stories from a mix of publications.

title: Facebook News launches with hand-picked stories from major publishers
text: Facebook on Friday announced the launch of Facebook News, a new section of the social network that will show users a personalized selection of news stories.

title: The techno-utopian visions of Google and Facebook are dead. What comes next?
text:
Today’s big tech companies need to embrace a new philosophy: techno-pragmatism.
Just earlier this month, while meeting with Congress to discuss digital privacy, censorship, and transparency, Republican Senator Josh Hawley asked Facebook’s Mark Zuckerberg to divest of WhatsApp and Instagram.
